It was continued (according to Cramer, who quotes Dion Halic. iv. 54) by Tarquinius Priscus as far as the Porta Querquetulana, being in all about twelve stadia, and about fifty feet in breadth. It thus skirted on the east the whole of the fifth or Esquiline quarter3 and the sixth‚ which had its name Alta Semita from this great work. Here the Romans walked in cold westher to get the sun, and had a full view of the pestilent plain which Maecenas converted into a paradise. Juvenal calls it ‘ventosus’ (S. viii. 43). Bentley edits ⁴ qua’ in v. 15, and is followed by some editors. It is against all the MSS. and older editions, and ‘ quo,' in the sense of ⁸ ex quo,’ will do very well.

17. Cum milas· non tantum] ‘ Cum’ is thus connected with what goes before. Priapus says the lomlity is now made healthy. and the citizens may take their walk without being sickened with the sight of bones bleaching upon the plain, whereas his vexations still remain‚—-the driving away of thieves and wild animals which still fre- quented the spot, and yet worse the punish- ment and scaring away of the witches who there continued to carry on their abominable practices. We need not infer with Dacier that the place was not yet entirely changed or cleared of the bones that disfigured it, but may suppose the witches still continued from habit to haunt the scene of their ini- quities, and that the ‘fiires ' and ‘ferae,’ are the depredators that came to rob the gardens which were the god’s particular care. 1 am not aware of any other instance of ‘ suetus ’ being used as a trisyllable.
